//   * timeline year labels fail contrast        (color-contrast)
//   * heading jumps h1 -> h3                     (heading-order)
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Pluto's Years as a Planet" description="The 76 years Pluto spent as the Solar System's ninth planet.">
  <h1>Pluto's 76 Years as a Planet</h1>
  <p>
    From its discovery in 1930 until 2006, Pluto was taught to schoolchildren
    everywhere as the ninth and most distant planet of the Solar System. Its
    status, however, was questioned almost from the very beginning.
  </p>

  <!-- Skipped heading level: h1 above, h3 here (no h2) -->
  <h3>A planet from the start</h3>
  <p>
    When Pluto was found, astronomers assumed it was roughly the size of Earth —
    large enough to disturb Neptune's orbit. Over the following decades, better
    measurements shrank Pluto dramatically, until it was known to be smaller than
    our own Moon.
  </p>

  <!-- The "timeline" is a <ul> whose children are <div>, not <li> (list rule).
       Year labels use .year-fail (color-contrast). -->
  <ul class="timeline">
    <div class="entry"><span class="year year-fail">1930</span> Clyde Tombaugh discovers Pluto; it is hailed as the ninth planet.</div>
    <div class="entry"><span class="year year-fail">1978</span> Pluto's large moon Charon is discovered, allowing Pluto's mass to be measured — and it is tiny.</div>
    <div class="entry"><span class="year year-fail">1992</span> The first other Kuiper Belt object is found, hinting that Pluto has many neighbours.</div>
    <div class="entry"><span class="year year-fail">2005</span> Eris, a Kuiper Belt object more massive than Pluto, is discovered.</div>
    <div class="entry"><span class="year year-fail">2006</span> The International Astronomical Union defines "planet" and reclassifies Pluto as a dwarf planet.</div>
  </ul>

  <h2>The trouble with being ninth</h2>
  <p>
    As telescopes improved, astronomers realised Pluto was just one of many icy
    bodies in the Kuiper Belt. If Pluto counted as a planet, so might dozens of
    similar objects. The discovery of Eris — at first thought to be larger than
    Pluto — finally forced the question: what exactly <em>is</em> a planet?
  </p>
  <p>
    That question was answered in 2006, and the answer left Pluto on the outside.
    Read more about <a href="/demotion">Pluto's demotion</a>.
  </p>
</Layout>
